toman Regencies of Algiers and Constantine in the 1830s helped lay the groundwork for the creation of a new identity for French military and civilian settlers.Effros uses France’s violent colonial war, its efforts to document the ancient Roman past, and its brutal treatment of the region’s Arab and Berber inhabitants to underline the close entanglement of knowledge production with European imperialism. Significantly, Incidental Archaeologists shows how the French experience in Algeria contributed to the professionalization of archaeology in metropolitan France.Effros demonstrates how the archaeological expeditions undertaken by the French in Algeria and the documentation they collected of ancient Roman military accomplishments reflected French confidence that they would learn from Rome’s technological accomplishments and succeed, where the Romans had failed, in mastering the region.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAlgeria-Antiquities, Roman. 0aAlgeria-History-1830-1962. 0aArchaeology and statezFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aArchaeology and state-France-History-19th century. 0aArchaeologyxPolitical aspectszAlgeriaxHistoryy19th century. 0aArchaeologyxPolitical aspectszFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aArchaeology-Political aspects-Algeria-History-19th century. 0aArchaeology-Political aspects-France-History-19th century. 0aFrance-Armed Forces-Algeria-Operations other than war-History-19th century. 4aArchaeology. 4aHistory. 4aWest European History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / France.2bisacsh  aAlgeria, colonial archaeology, Roman archaeology, French colonialism, military archaeology.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz9783110604252